{"cursor":"21156","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n{{Infobox\n| bodyclass = geography abovestyle = background:#DEB887; subheader = Ancient\n| Region of Anatolia above = Pontus (Î ÏÎ½ÏÎ¿Ï) image = caption = Traditional rural\n| Pontic house label1 = Location data1 = North-eastern Anatolia label2 = Ethnic\n| Groups data2 = Pontic Greeks, Laz, HemÅin, Chepni, Turks label3 = Historical\n| capitals data3 = Amasya, Neocaesarea, Sinope, Trabzon label4 = Notable rulers\n| data4 = Mithradates Eupator data8 = The modern definition of the\n| Pontus: the area claimed for the \"Republic of Pontus\" after World War I, based\n| on the extent of the six local Greek Orthodox bishoprics.\n}} 'Pontus' (; , \"sea\", [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perse-\nus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0057%3Aentry%3Dpo%2Fntos ÏÏÎ½ÏÎ¿Ï], Henry George Liddell,\nRobert Scott, A Greek-English Lexicon, on Perseus ) is a historical Greek\ndesignation for a region on the southern coast of the Black Sea, located in modern-\nday northeastern Turkey. The name was applied to the coastal region in antiquity\nby the Greeks who colonized the area, and derived from the Greek name of the\nBlack Sea: Î ÏÎ½ÏÎ¿Ï ÎÏÎ¾ÎµÎ¹Î½Î¿Ï Pontos Euxeinos (\"Hospitable Sea\" [http://www.pe-\nrseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0072%3Aentry%3D*eu%29%-\n2Fceinos Îá½Î¾ÎµÎ¹Î½Î¿Ï], William J. Slater, Lexicon to Pindar, on Perseus ), or\nsimply Pontos. Having originally no specific name, the region east of the river\nHalys was spoken of as the country ÎµÎ½ Î ÏÎ½ÏÎ¿Î¹ en PontÃ´i, \"on the [Euxeinos]\nPontos\", and hence acquired the name of Pontus, which is first found in\nXenophon's [[Anabasis (Xenophon)|Anabasis]]. The extent of the region varied\nthrough the ages, but generally it extended from the borders of Colchis (modern\nGeorgia) until well into Paphlagonia in the west, with varying amounts of\nhinterland. Several states and provinces bearing the name of Pontus or variants\nthereof were established in the region in Hellenistic, Roman and Byzantine\ntimes. Pontus is known for the residence of the Amazons, with the name Amasia\nnot only used for a city (Amasya) but for all of Pontus in Greek mythology.\n","linknr":958,"url":"Pontus","recorded":1375083648,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Pontus&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Pontus&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Greek_mythology","/wiki/Pontus_(mythology)","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pontus&action=edit","/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing/1","/wiki/Template:Citation_needed","/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence","/wiki/File:Evler2b.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/16/Evler2b.jpg/250px-Evler2b.jpg","/wiki/Anatolia","/wiki/Pontic_Greeks","/wiki/Laz_people","/wiki/Hemshin_peoples","/wiki/Chepni","/wiki/Turkish_people","/wiki/Amasya","/wiki/Neocaesarea","/wiki/Sinop,_Turkey","/wiki/Trabzon","/wiki/Mithradates_Eupator","/wiki/File:Pontus.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/55/Pontus.png/250px-Pontus.png","/wiki/Republic_of_Pontus","/wiki/World_W